<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
Presumably trailing herb of unknown length; stems and leaves pubescent. Leaves similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mill., Gard. Dict. ed. 8: no. 20. 1768. (Miller" authorityYear="1768" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus betonicifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betonicifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Convolvulus betonicifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, petiolate, c. 2.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2 cm, ovate, obtuse and mucronate, entire, shallowly sagittate with short auricles. Flowers 1-2, pedunculate, axillary; peduncles c. 2.5 cm; bracteoles c. 5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5 mm, linear, attenuate; pedicels equalling bracts; sepals 6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm, oblong-oblanceolate, obtuse and retuse, mucronulate, pubescent, inner sepals glabrous, membranous; corolla 2.5 cm long, colour unknown, midpetaline bands pubescent, unlobed; filaments glandular below; ovary glabrous, style 8 mm long, glabrous, stigmas 5 mm. Capsule and seeds unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Turkey. Only known from the type collection.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
This species is not conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis" order="Solanales" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Convolvulus arvensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as stated in the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Flora of Turkey</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Parris, BS" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Turkey" pageId="208" pageNumber="209" pagination="198 - 219" refId="B256" refString="Parris, BS, 1978. Convolvulus. Flora of Turkey volume 6: 198 - 219" title="Convolvulus." volume="volume 6" year="1978">Parris 1978</bibRefCitation>
) but differs in the pubescent leaves and the pubescent, 6 mm long, herbaceous sepals which lack a membranous border. Instead it is clearly related to the very variable 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mill., Gard. Dict. ed. 8: no. 20. 1768. (Miller" authorityYear="1768" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus betonicifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betonicifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Convolvulus betonicifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as stated by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
, but appears to be distinct as we cannot match it with any specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mill., Gard. Dict. ed. 8: no. 20. 1768. (Miller" authorityYear="1768" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus betonicifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betonicifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Convolvulus betonicifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs in the shorter, obtuse and minutely retuse sepals 5-6 mm long, which lack a distinctive apical portion. The ovary is also glabrous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
